  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Some key aspects of AML regulations include:\n\n1. Banks and financial institutions must:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Conduct due diligence on customers\n\n2. Major regulatory frameworks include:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (USA)\n- EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Proceeds of Crime Act (UK)\n\n3. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Significant financial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of business licenses\n\n4. These regulations apply to various sectors, including:\n- Banking\n- Financial services\n- Real estate\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n- Casino and gambling industries\n\nThe specific details and implementation of AML regulations vary by country, but the overall goal is to detect and prevent financial crimes.",
